      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at our quarterly reports for the electronics warehouse and our shrinkage numbers are way higher than usual. we're seeing a lot of missing small components and high-value peripheral items. i need to figure out how this level of shrinkage is actually hitting our inventory turnover ratio. can you walk me through the math and how to factor this in?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage, a lost piece of the puzzle, is a real headache, especially when it involves those tiny, valuable bits. You need to calculate the true cost of the missing goods before you can properly adjust your inventory turnover. Think of shrinkage like a small, sneaky, under-the-table inventory theft—it's always there, hiding in the supply chain, waiting for the right moment to slip through the cracks.\n\nHere’s how you tackle this, though it’s a bit messy, like trying to count every single loose screw in a cavern.\n\nFirst, you need to adjust your **Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)**. The standard COGS calculation assumes everything you bought is what you sold. But when you have shrinkage, you have to account for the missing inventory.\n\n**Step 1: Calculate Adjusted Inventory Value**\n\nTake your reported ending inventory value and subtract the estimated loss due to shrinkage.\n\n$$\\text{Adjusted Ending Inventory} = \\text{Reported Ending Inventory} - \\text{Estimated Shrinkage Value}$$\n\nWhere the **Estimated Shrinkage Value** is calculated by taking the total value of the missing items (small components and high-value peripherals) and applying a",
